## Key Takeaways

<StepByStep title="ADHD and Movement: Core Insights">
<Step title="Dopamine and norepinephrine are the key">
Exercise increases the same neurotransmitters targeted by ADHD medications. This improves attention, motivation, impulse control, and executive function.
</Step>

<Step title="Both acute and chronic effects are documented">
A single session improves focus for 40-60 minutes post-exercise. Regular training produces sustained symptom reduction over weeks to months.
</Step>

<Step title="Timing matters: Pre-task focus priming">
20-30 minutes of moderate-vigorous aerobic exercise *before* cognitively demanding tasks maximizes the focus window.
</Step>

<Step title="Skill-based movement may outperform simple cardio">
Martial arts, dance, rock climbing, team sports — activities that require cognitive demand alongside physical exertion — enhance executive function more than repetitive aerobic exercise alone.
</Step>

<Step title="Fidgeting is a feature, not a bug">
Allowing low-level movement (standing desk, fidget tools, walking meetings) *during* tasks improves focus in ADHD — stillness is cognitively costly.
</Step>

<Step title="Exercise is an adjunct, not a replacement">
Movement supports medication and behavioral therapy — it doesn't replace them. Work with your healthcare provider for comprehensive ADHD management.
</Step>
</StepByStep>

